Description: Six big sherds five of them rim sherds, handmade, Nubian, from different vessels, Kerma Moyen? A: AWS 537, P/D? Body sherd with finger tip impressions on the outside. Illegible word written on the inside. B: AWS 197, Site D. Rim-sherd of a closed vessel with the rim folded over. Vertical incised lines along the rim. C: AWS 452, Cem. D. Rim-sherd of a bowl, roughly made, incised lines at the outside, roughly triangles with lines. D: AWS 459, Cem. D. Rim-sherd of a bowl, incised lines at the outside, filling a pattern of triangles with lines. E: AWS 460, Cem. D. Rim-sherd of a bowl, incised lines at the outside, filling a pattern of triangles with lines. F: AW 38/39, Site D, Am. P. 12. Large rim-sherd of a bowl, incised lines at the outside, filling a pattern of triangles with lines. A white substance at the outside.
Findspot: Excavated/Findspot: Amara West (Nubia), Various locations, including Cemetery D
Dimensions: Height: 10.10 centimetres (Measurements refer to largest glued fragment)
Acquisition notes: Formerly housed by the Birmingham Museum and Art Gallery and the EES London.
